A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow down the spread of the HIV virus in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works for the viruses that have already obtained immunity against the drugs.
This fact outweighs in some cases that the compound does not feel as strong on the common variant of the virus as some of the drugs already available.
AIDS disease cannot yet be cured.
However, patients can be significantly prolonged by a mixture of drugs that prevent the multiplication of the HIV virus in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, the incomplete suppression of the virus's propagation results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which the drugs are no longer inactive.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, from the University of Technology in Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with the resistance of the virus.
They demonstrated that substances called metocarboran act on the protein responsible for the HIV virus to multiply.
Metalocarboran are boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt compounds.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all the drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new 'encaped' compounds prepared based on the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to viral protein.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-dimensional cages made up of boron atoms, hydrogen and carbon are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein for the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
