The Turkish judiciary has dissolved the Kurdish side, and the decision carries severe consequences.
Turkey's Constitutional Court on Friday decided to abolish the country's main pro-Kurdish party, and this decision immediately triggered protest demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of a government seeking to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand to try to end the 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society (DTP) party was dissolved because it became a "price of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," Chief Justice Chief Justice Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of negotiations.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, when it took a majority-seven vote to dissolve the party, Kiliç said, adding that the 37 party cadres, including its president, Ahmet Türk, and MEP Aysela Tugluk, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the annulment of the parliamentary immunity of Mr Türk and Ms Tugluk and the confiscation of the assets of the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP has 21 seats in the Parliament (of 500).
The party leadership had already warned before the verdict that MPs would rather leave Parliament than act as MPs without political affiliation.
The decision is a continuation of the trial initiated in 2007 by the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation, Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses DTP of obedience to the "guides" of the Workers' Party of Kurdistan (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organisation.
Many observers believe that DTP is a legal political case for the rebels of the PKK.
The party assures that it has no "farea link" with the PKK, but refuses to label it as a terrorist organisation and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court's verdict comes as the government gives the Kurdish community a friendly hand and offers a series of measures to strengthen their rights and attempt to limit the support of the Kurds against the PKK to end the conflict.
DTP leadership has confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to a resumption of tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations have degenerated in recent weeks against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is being held into clashes with the police.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of demonstrators have gathered outside the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large town in the southeast that are inhabited mainly by the Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water cannons, and protesters threw Molotov cocktails or shot stones from slingshots.
Also in Istanbul, about a hundred people demonstrated.
After the verdict was reached, Mr Türk said that the justice decision would only "whip overtake despair."
Turkey cannot resolve this issue with a ban on the party, he said in the press.
The government, formed by the party arising from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are against the disrupting of the parties.
It solves nothing, said Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete shattering of democratic proposals launched by the government, commented political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we may see a reaction from the PKK, he added.
